<HEAD>Mass Brings Promise for Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MARLENE AIG</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduran President <PERSON>Rafael Leonardo Callejas</PERSON> said
<DATE>Friday</DATE> his country was donating <MONEY>$25,000</MONEY> to build a recreation
center in the neighborhood where 87 people died when fire swept
through an illegal social club.
   Cardinal <PERSON>John O'Connor</PERSON> said the archdiocese of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> also was
committed to building the center to diminish the need for illegal
social clubs in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> neighborhood.
   The announcements were made at a memorial Mass for the victims
of the <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> tragedy.
   Callejas told the more than 750 people inside <ORGANIZATION>St. Thomas Aquinas
Church</ORGANIZATION> and more than 100 people listening through loudspeakers
outside that the Honduran people raised the money, and that <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY>
of it was from his own pocket.
   <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON> said the church would match the contribution if the
city would donate the land. He promised to donate <MONEY>$999.99</MONEY> of his
own.
   Most of the 87 people who died <DATE>March 25</DATE> when fire ravaged the
club were Honduran immigrants.
   <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, 36, a Cuban immigrant, has been charged with
setting the blaze.
   The Mass, originally scheduled for <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>St. Patrick's
Cathedral</ORGANIZATION>, was shifted to <LOCATION>St. Thomas</LOCATION>, two blocks from the gutted
social club building, so Callejas could attend, officials said.
   ``Too many immigrants in our country are forced to live in
crowded, inadequate and dangerous housing conditions,'' <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON>,
speaking in Spanish, told families and friends of the victims.
   These immigrants have menial jobs because they are illegal, and
``it comes as no surprise that they are forced to use crowded and
dangerous facilities for various forms of social activities because
they are so poor,'' <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON> said.
   Callejas told the crowd that ``we are together in your pain.''
</TEXT>
