<LEADPARA>  The man who set a fire that killed 87 people at a social club received
Thursday the maximum sentence for murder: 25 years to life in prison.;  
Before issuing the sentence, Chief Judge Burton Roberts of the trial-level
Bronx State Supreme Court said so many people had died that "it becomes sort
of distant. We can't recognize the horrendous tragedy."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MAN IS GIVEN 25 YEARS TO LIFE FOR N.Y. CLUB FIRE
THAT KILLED 87  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, 37, was convicted of 174 counts of murder -- two counts for
each death. He got 25 years to life for each count, but the sentences will run
concurrently.;   Under state law, when multiple crimes arise out of a single
act, sentences cannot be consecutive. He will be eligible for parole in 25
years.;   Fight with ex-girlfriend; <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> set the fire at the Happy Land
club in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> on <DATE>March 25, 1990</DATE>, after he had a fight with an
ex-girlfriend who worked there and was kicked out by a bouncer.;   Attending
the sentencing were nearly 100 relatives and friends of the victims, many of
whom were immigrants from <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>. They applauded loudly at the sentence.;  
"I hope that he rots in jail," said <PERSON>Maria Clavijo</PERSON>, whose teen-age brother,
<PERSON>Juan Jose Nunez</PERSON>, died in the fire.;   Some were unhappy with the sentence,
even though it was the maximum permitted by law.;   "It's not enough -- he
deserved the death penalty," said <PERSON>Aracely Sanchez</PERSON>, who lost several cousins
and friends in the fire.;   Victims' stories; Before the sentencing, <PERSON>Roberts</PERSON>
recounted the stories of some of the victims. They included a sister and
brother who had been sending <MONEY>$200</MONEY> every two weeks to their mother in <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>
and a man who worked two jobs as a dishwasher and factory worker and who had a
pregnant wife.;   The club had been ordered closed for fire safety code
violations months before the blaze.;   "There are many to be blamed, not just
<PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON> with a 79 IQ who lost his head because he was insulted in front
of his live-in girlfriend," <PERSON>Roberts</PERSON> said.;   The fire spurred city officials
to create a <ORGANIZATION>Social Club Task Force</ORGANIZATION> that closed hundreds of illegal, unsafe
clubs around the city.;   Gasoline and matches; "There never should be a
tragedy such as this, which can be caused by a dollar's worth of gasoline and
two matches," <PERSON>Roberts</PERSON> said.;   The two counts of murder for each death
included one for depraved indifference and one for felony murder. Roberts also
sentenced <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> to 25 years to life for arson and five to 15 years for
assault.;   <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> told the judge he wanted to retain his attorney, <PERSON>Richard
Bern</PERSON>, to file an appeal.;   The jury rejected the defense argument that
<PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> was insane the night of the fire.;   District Attorney <PERSON>Robert Johnson</PERSON>
also said the state's maximum penalty was not enough. "There should be life
without parole," he said.  </TEXT>
