<FILEID>AP-NR-04-02-90 0826EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SocialClubFire     04-02 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Club Fire,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: City Owns At Least 52 Buildings Housing Clubs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION>'s government has been branded the
largest single landlord of illegal social clubs.
   At least 52 social clubs listed by the city as ``nuisance''
establishments are on city-owned property, according to reports
published in weekend newspapers.
   A police crackdown on the clubs started after 87 people, mostly
Hondurans, died <DATE>March 25</DATE> in an arson fire at the illegal <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land
Social Club</ORGANIZATION> in the Tremont section of the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION>.
   The bodies of 48 of the victims arrived <DATE>Sunday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION> for
burial.
   ``Most of them went to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> with high hopes, and
they came back dead. We are very sad,'' said President <PERSON>Rafael
Leonardo Callejas</PERSON>, who joined dozens of mourning relatives at the
airport at <LOCATION>San Pedro Sula</LOCATION>.
   Wakes and funerals were scheduled in 11 towns in northern
<LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Sunday</DATE> that police documents list at
least 52 clubs as ``nuisance'' establishments in properties owned
by the city, including two in city housing projects. That would
make the city the largest single landlord of such clubs.
   In late editions <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Daily News</ORGANIZATION> reported that as many
as 46 illegal clubs are located in city-owned residential
buildings. It based its report on a review of <ORGANIZATION>Buildings Department</ORGANIZATION>
and real estate records as well as inspections by city agencies.
   <PERSON>Lee Jones</PERSON>, a spokesman for Mayor <PERSON>David Dinkins</PERSON>, said the city
inherited the clubs along with vast numbers of tenants and
abandoned buildings.
   ``Is it embarrassing?'' Jones said. ``It's something we're going
to have to deal with.''
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900412-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-90 0539EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SocialClubFire     04-12 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Club Fire,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Club Fire Suspect Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged in an illegal nightspot fire that
killed 87 people pleaded innocent today to 174 counts of murder and
other charges.
   <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, 36, was guarded by four armed court officers as
he was arraigned before <PERSON>Judge Burton R. Roberts</PERSON> in trial-level
state <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION>.
   Gonzalez, who spoke to the court through a Spanish translator,
mumbled ``no culpable'' when asked how he pleaded on the charges.
   The judge told attorneys that under state law, <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> could
serve only a single 25 years-to-life sentence even if convicted on
all charges. The law stipulates his sentences would have to run
concurrently, <PERSON>Roberts</PERSON> said.
   Gonzalez is accused of setting a fire that trapped revelers
inside the tiny <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION>.
   Authorities charge that the Cuban immigrant, enraged by the
rejection of a former girlfriend who worked at the club, bought <MONEY>$1</MONEY>
worth of gasoline, spilled it in the illegal club's doorway and set
it aflame. Only five people escaped the cramped club following the
<TIME>4 a.m.</TIME> fire, including the girlfriend.
   Court-appointed defense attorney <PERSON>Richard W. Berne</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE> he
had not decided whether to use an insanity defense for his client,
although he had indicated earlier that was a possibility.
   <PERSON>Berne</PERSON> said he plans to ask for a dismissal of all charges
against <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> because the lawyer was not given access to a
videotaped confession by his client when the case was submitted to
the grand jury.
   Gonzalez was indicted <DATE>March 30</DATE> on 174 counts of murder, two
counts of arson and single counts of attempted murder and assault.
He was charged with two separate murder counts for each of the
victims killed in the social club blaze.
   The club lacked proper permits and did not have adequate exits
and sprinkling systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900403-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-03-90 0842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SocialClubFire     04-03 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Club Fire,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Arrest Warrant Was Outstanding For Happy Land Owner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arrest warrant was issued last year for the
owner of the building that housed a club where 87 people died by
fire, but he never was arrested, city records show.
   A <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> criminal judge issued the warrant after the owner, <PERSON>Alex
DiLorenzo III</PERSON>, failed to appear for a hearing on fire code
violations at the illegal social club, The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> reported
in today's editions.
   The warrant for <PERSON>DiLorenzo</PERSON>, who is an heir to one of the city's
largest real estate fortunes, was low priority and never was
enforced, police said.
   ``We are interested in all warrants,'' said Lt. <PERSON>Raymond
O'Donnell</PERSON>, a police spokesman. ``But we are more interested in
going after the guy who has committed a murder over a guy who has
violations in a building.''
   Of 100,000 yearly arrest warrants, those for building code
violations are among the lowest priority, <PERSON>O'Donnell</PERSON> said.
   The warrant for <PERSON>DiLorenzo</PERSON> was issued <DATE>Feb. 3, 1989</DATE>, by <ORGANIZATION>Bronx
Criminal Court</ORGANIZATION> <PERSON>Judge James E. Robinson</PERSON>. The violations listed in
the warrant carried a fine of up to <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY> and 90 days in jail.
   The club lacked adequate sprinklers, emergency lighting and an
assembly permit for the entertainment of more than 75 people.
   A task force created by the city in <DATE>1988</DATE> after another fatal
social club fire inspected Happy Land on <DATE>Nov. 20, 1988</DATE>, and ordered
it closed.
   DiLorenzo has not returned telephone calls placed to his office
over the past several days, the newspaper said.
   The man who allegedly set the fire, <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, was being
held in the psychiatric unit in the prison wing at <ORGANIZATION>Bellevue
Hospital</ORGANIZATION>.
   A friend of <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>'s, <PERSON>Juana Ortiz</PERSON>, told the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> Post he
was stricken with grief when told that one of his best friends died
in the <DATE>March 25</DATE> fire at <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION>.
   The friend, identified only as <ORGANIZATION>Ramon</ORGANIZATION>, had comforted <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>
after he was evicted by the club's bouncer before the fire, <PERSON>Ms.
Ortiz</PERSON> said.
   She said when she told Gonzlalez that <PERSON>Ramon</PERSON> had died, he shouted
``Oh my God! Please forgive me!'' and broke down sobbing, the
newspaper reported in today's editions.
   <PERSON>Ortiz</PERSON> said <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> is resigned to punishment and spends his day
reading a Spanish-language Bible.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900326-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-26-90 0606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fire-Neighborhood     03-26 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire-Neighborhood,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran Community Mourns Fire Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Social Club Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERENA DOBNIK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wails and cries echoed from inside a school
where friends and relatives gathered to confirm their worst fears _
that one of the 87 who died in a <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> fire was their daughter,
husband, lover.
   Many emerged pale and distraught from <ORGANIZATION>Public School</ORGANIZATION> 67 after
identifying dead family members in photos.
   A Honduran flag was draped over a fence outside the school; many
of those who died were immigrants from <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   ``They tried to live the American dream: to get a job and make
something of themselves,'' said <PERSON>Cheo Garcia</PERSON>, a former patron of the
Happy Land social club.
   ``They all dreamed of returning home _ but with more money,''
said <PERSON>Miguel Reyes</PERSON>, coach of <ORGANIZATION>Club Deportivo Adrana</ORGANIZATION>, an amateur
soccer team.
   Reyes counted team members among the dead: <PERSON>Orvin Garbutt</PERSON>, 22,
<PERSON>Bagoberto Echeverri</PERSON>, 18, and a third player, all from <LOCATION>Puerto
Cortez</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   They lived in <LOCATION>East Tremont</LOCATION>, a neighborhood populated by
Hondurans, Dominicans, <LOCATION>Puerto Ricans</LOCATION> and Ecuadorans.
   The area is blighted by poor housing, drugs, unemployment and
truancy. Graffitti marred the rolled-down security gates on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>
as trash blew down streets and across vacant lots. A rat lay dead
on the sidewalk.
   Bronx Borough President <PERSON>Fernando Ferrer</PERSON> said the neighborhood
did not have an especially high crime rate. But some young men were
snorting cocaine in full view of police officers.
   Residents are trying to renovate the impoverished area, said the
Rev. <PERSON>Ruben Diaz</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Christian Community Benevolent Association</ORGANIZATION>,
a Protestant group.
   On <DATE>Saturday</DATE> nights, some took a break and flocked to an illegal
social club called Happy Land.
   ``We have to try hard to close these places. They are killing
our people,'' <PERSON>Diaz</PERSON> said. ``Sometimes we say, let them have it
because they have nothing better. Now we have to say, 'What is more
important, to have a good time or to stay alive?'''
   About 1,000 people gathered outside Happy Land, next to a union
hiring hall where the victims' bodies were assembled in rows on the
floor.
   Loved ones were allowed through police lines to look at the
photos at <LOCATION>P.S.</LOCATION> 67.
   ``We're looking for friends and relatives and nobody's telling
us anything,'' complained <PERSON>Rosemary Green</PERSON>, who believed her
sister-in-law and cousin had gone to Happy Land.
   ``It's a slow process,'' said the Rev. <PERSON>A.B. Duncans</PERSON>, pastor of
the nearby <ORGANIZATION>First Glorious Church Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, who was assisting and
counseling some of the bereaved.
   One woman collapsed on the sidewalk outside the school and had
to be helped inside, where her son's picture was displayed with
those of other victims.
   <PERSON>Jorge Pineda</PERSON> lost five friends, all from <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   A friend called <PERSON>Pineda</PERSON>'s apartment at <TIME>8 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, and asked
his wife if he was going, as usual, to the <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> dance.
   Pineda's wife hung up; she didn't approve of the place. Eight
hours later, <PERSON>Pineda</PERSON> was identifying his friends' bodies from police
photos.
   ``I'm the only friend they had,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900419-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-90 0040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SocialClubFire     04-19 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Club Fire,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Lawyer Who Filed Club's Papers Is A Cop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer who filed incorporation papers for
the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> social club where 87 people died in a fire is a city
police lieutenant who is now himself under investigation, according
to a published report.
   Lt. <PERSON>Primo Flores</PERSON> was moonlighting as a lawyer when he listed the
Happy Land club as a not-for-profit corporation in the <DATE>1988</DATE> papers,
The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> reported in <DATE>Thursday</DATE> editions.
   Nothing suggests <PERSON>Flores</PERSON> knew the club would sell liquor
illegally and operate in violation of city orders that it close
because of building violations, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Police told the Times that the investigation is aimed at
determining whether <PERSON>Flores</PERSON> adhered to departmental requirements to
disclose his outside business activities and whether he had
committed any wrongdoing in his work for the club.
   Flores' role in setting up the club has been under investigation
by the <ORGANIZATION>Police Department's Internal Affairs Division</ORGANIZATION> since shortly
after the <DATE>March 25</DATE> fire, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The 48-year-old <PERSON>Flores</PERSON>, a policeman since <DATE>1967</DATE>, works in the
<ORGANIZATION>Police Department</ORGANIZATION>'s Advocate office, which prosecutes departmental
charges against police officers accused of breaking regulations.
   Flores did not return calls requesting comment, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   A Cuban immigrant, <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, has been charged with setting
the deadly blaze after a dispute with his girlfriend, who worked at
the club as a coat checker.
   The club had been operating in violation of vacate orders issued
after city inspectors discovered there was no second exit, no fire
alarms and inadequate sprinklers.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900406-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-90 1750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SocialClubFire     04-06 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Social Club Fire,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Club Fire Survivor, Haunted, Hanging on</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY46</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nightmares jolt <PERSON>Ruben Valladarez</PERSON> awake in his
hospital bed, tormenting him with thoughts of friends who died in a
place called Happy Land.
   ``I feel better,'' he said <DATE>Friday</DATE>. ``Only I got a little bad
dreams.''
   Valladarez, the disc jockey at the illegal <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> social club, is
one of a few survivors of the arson fire that killed 87 people
<DATE>March 25</DATE>. He was critically injured, with burns over <PERCENT>40 percent</PERCENT> of
his body.
   In his first interview, <PERSON>Valladarez</PERSON> described the ordeal
haltingly, with tears. He lost friends, and at least three cousins,
he said, naming them with a tortured face. He cannot explain why he
was the one who lived.
   He was spinning records in the back, on the second floor, about
<TIME>4 a.m.</TIME> ``Somebody screamed _ `Fire!''' Valladarez recalled. ``I put
the lights on. I said into the microphone, ``Everybody get out!
I've got a fire!''
   There was no emergency exit at the crowded club, no emergency
lights, no sprinkler system, not even a window to jump from.
Valladarez was one of only two people to escape from the second
floor. Four or more escaped from the first floor.
   First he crossed to the front of the second-floor dance area,
looking for a friend. ``I said, `We have to get out, man.''' He
descended a narrow front stairway to the first floor bar. It was
already filled with flames.
   ``Downstairs is fire. I run downstairs,'' said <PERSON>Valladarez</PERSON>, 26, a
native of Trujillo, <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>, for whom English is a second language.
   People there were running about in panic. ``They scream.
Everybody going to the door, pushing the door. It's locked.''
   Valladarez thought of his wife, <PERSON>Frances</PERSON>, and their 2-year-old
daughter, <PERSON>Nadine</PERSON>. He ran into the flames, searching for the sole
open door; there was no other choice. ``I had to go,'' he said.
   When Valladarez reached the street his clothes were on fire.
People threw water on him. He suffered third-degree burns on his
forearms and hands, second-degree burns on his legs and face.
   When his wife saw him at <ORGANIZATION>Bronx Municipal Hospital</ORGANIZATION> she could not
recognize him.
   Twelve days and three operations later, <ORGANIZATION>Valladarez</ORGANIZATION> remains in
critical condition in the burn ward. He may need more surgery, and
two to three months of hospitalization, and nine to 18 months of
rehabilitation. The burn ward chief, <PERSON>Dr. Steven Blau</PERSON>, said it is
too soon to say whether Valladarez will regain the use of his hands.
   ``His attitude is very good. He's a fighter,'' <PERSON>Blau</PERSON> said. ``And
his attitude is very important, because everything he has to do in
terms of recovery will hurt him.''
   Valladarez's face is raw, blistered under the eyebrows and on
his lips, coated with salve. A tube feeds oxygen into his nose. Two
needles provide intravenous fluid. His arms are heavily bandaged,
one suspended from a stand to keep swelling down. He is hooked up
to a heart monitor.
   He said he feels anguish for loved ones who died and anger at
<PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, the man accused of setting the fire to punish an
ex-girlfriend who worked there.
   ``He has to go to jail. Fifty years _ or 200,'' <PERSON>Valladarez</PERSON> said.
``In my country, this man is die.''
   Valladarez, who worked at the Happy Land for two years, said he
never had considered the danger of fire there.
   His advice now: Stay away. ``Don't go no more. Because every
social club in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> is bad.''
</TEXT>
