<DESCRIPT>  NEW-YORK; UNUSUAL; ARSON; FIRE; MURDER; TRIAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A man accused of setting a fire that killed 87 people went on trial today, and
a judge ruled that prosecutors can use the man's confessions.;    Supreme
Court Justice Burton Roberts said he was satisfied that three statements by
Julio Gonzalez were not the result of police pressure.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AS ARSON TRIAL BEGINS, JUDGE OKS CONFESSIONS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     All but a handful of patrons were trapped and died when fire raced through
the cramped, two-story <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> borough.;    <PERSON>Julio
Gonzalez</PERSON>, 37, has pleaded not guilty by reason of insanity. He faces 178
counts of murder, including two murder charges for each victim, in the <DATE>March
25, 1990</DATE>, fire. The other charges include attempted murder, arson and assault.
He is being tried in <LOCATION>trial-level state Supreme Court.</LOCATION>;    <PERSON>Richard Berne</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>'s court appointed defense attorney, said he was not surprised by the
judge's decision, which preceded jury selection. The defense had moved to
suppress the confessions and physical evidence.;    The three statements to
police include one that was videotaped soon after <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>'s arrest. On all
three, police say, <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> admitted that he had poured gasoline in the
entrance of the club and set it afire.;    Police say he admitted he set the
fire in anger after he was ejected from the club for harassing a former
girlfriend who worked there. She escaped.;    Most of the victims were
Hondurans who frequented Happy Land, one of many illegal after-hours clubs
then operating in the city.;    Fire and building inspectors had ordered the
club closed in <DATE>1988</DATE> because it lacked a fire alarm and sprinklers and had just
one exit.  </TEXT>
