<HEAD>Landlord Tried to Evict Happy Land Social Club</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Social Club Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to add rent figures for Happy Land and La
Salsa and to delete description of ex-girlfriend's job at club as
selling tickets because duties apparently varied. Picks up 15th
graf, `Neighborhood residents...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities had warned the owners of the
building that housed the <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> that it was riddled
with violations, including no sprinkler system on the first floor,
where the fire started.
   Notice of the fire code violations, which also included an
illegally added-on second floor, no second exit and no fire alarms,
were sent to <PERSON>Alex DiLorenzo III</PERSON>, the owner, building Commissioner
<PERSON>Charles Smith Jr.</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>The New York Times</ORGANIZATION> in today's editions.
   DiLorenzo leased the building to <PERSON>Jay Weiss</PERSON>, husband of actress
<PERSON>Kathleen Turner</PERSON>, who in turn leased the building to club manager
<PERSON>Elias Colon</PERSON>. Colon was among the 87 people who died in the fire
<DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   Normally, the violations report would have been forwarded by the
owner to the leaseholder, but <PERSON>Weiss</PERSON>' attorneys said they never
received a formal notice of the violations. They would not comment
on whether they knew of them.
   Prosecutors are looking into whether the building's landlords or
owners might bear responsibility for the fire. Police alleged it
was set by <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, in a jealous rage against his
ex-girlfriend, who worked at the club.
   The club was incorporated in <DATE>1988</DATE> as a not-for-profit
corporation for ``the purpose of providing for members
entertainment, sport, recreation and amusement of all kinds,'' the
Times reported.
   The incorporation papers appeared to enable Colon to avoid
filing state and city income tax forms, the <ORGANIZATION>Times</ORGANIZATION> said.
   <PERSON>Weiss</PERSON> had been trying to evict the <ORGANIZATION>Happy Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> for
non-payment of rent since <DATE>September</DATE>, according to <PERSON>Weiss</PERSON>' lawyer,
<PERSON>Roger Boyle</PERSON>.
   A lease signed by Happy Land on <DATE>Oct. 7, 1987</DATE>, called for monthly
rents of <MONEY>$1,500</MONEY> for the first year, <MONEY>$1,650</MONEY> for the second and
<MONEY>$1,950</MONEY> for the third.
   Court papers concerning the rent squabble show that on <DATE>Feb. 15,
1989</DATE>, a process server stuck a notice on the door of Happy Land
demanding <MONEY>$3,074</MONEY> within three days for rent payments allegedly due
since <DATE>Dec. 1, 1987</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Weiss</PERSON>' company, <ORGANIZATION>One Peach Associates</ORGANIZATION>, asked a marshal to obtain
an eviction notice on <DATE>Sept. 6, 1989</DATE>, according to the papers. A
judge validated the eviction warrant the next week and then Colon
filed to stop the proceedings, saying he had not seen the court
papers.
   Colon maintained in an affidavit that all his rent had been
paid. A judge granted a stay of the eviction warrant.
   Papers filed on <DATE>March 12</DATE> assert that <ORGANIZATION>Colon</ORGANIZATION> ``made substantial
improvements to the premises with the approval and consent of the
petitioner.''
   The case was to have been tried today.
   One Peach also leased space to La Salsa, another after-hours
club around the corner from Happy Land, for <MONEY>$2,500</MONEY> a month, the
<ORGANIZATION>Daily News</ORGANIZATION> said in today's editions.
   Neighborhood residents said La Salsa has one door and no
windows. Because of fire code violations, it had been ordered
closed on <DATE>Aug. 28, 1988</DATE>, the News reported.
   La Salsa was packed with revelers on the night of the fire at
Happy Land.
</TEXT>
