<HEAD>Suspect in Social-Club Arson Was an Army Deserter From Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed as an army deserter in <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>, the Mariel
refugee charged with setting the nightclub fire that killed 87
people was described as a street hustler who recently lost his job
and girlfriend.
   <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, 36, was moved <DATE>Monday</DATE> from the <LOCATION>Rikers Island</LOCATION> jail
to the psychiatric ward at <ORGANIZATION>Kings County Hospital</ORGANIZATION>, where he was
under a suicide watch, said <PERSON>Ruby Ryles</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the city
<ORGANIZATION>Corrections Department</ORGANIZATION>.
   Gonzalez, charged with murdering 87 people by torching the <ORGANIZATION>Happy
Land Social Club</ORGANIZATION> early <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, had no prior criminal record.
   Gonzalez told immigration officials when he arrived in the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> in <DATE>1980</DATE> that he had portrayed himself as a drug
trafficker to Cuban authorities in order to get kicked out of <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>,
<PERSON>Duke Austin</PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Immigration and Naturalization
Service</ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION>The New York Times</ORGANIZATION>.
   There was no evidence <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> was involved with drugs here,
officials said.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials have complained that many of the 125,000 people
kicked out of <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION> in the boatlift had criminal records or mental
disorders. Others were simply dissatisfied with life in <LOCATION>Cuba</LOCATION>.
   Gonzalez reportedly lost his last job, at a lamp factory, about
six months ago. Detective <PERSON>James Malvey</PERSON> said <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> since had
hustled money washing cars and peddling.
   For the past three months <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> has lived in an <MONEY>$80-a-week</MONEY>
furnished room in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION>. Before that he had lived with
45-year-old <PERSON>Lydia Feliciano</PERSON>.
   ``He was just a normal guy,'' said <PERSON>Ray Davis</PERSON>, the building
manager. ``He's a nice, quiet, clean guy.''
   Gonzalez allegedly told police he torched the club after
quarreling with <PERSON>Ms. Feliciano</PERSON>.
   <PERSON>Franco Mena</PERSON>, who showed up at the club after the fire, said he
and another man prevailed on <PERSON>Ms. Feliciano</PERSON> to identify <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> as
the arsonist. ``She didn't want to talk because she thought nobody
had heard her argument,'' <PERSON>Mena</PERSON> said.
   Bronx District Attorney <PERSON>Robert Johnson</PERSON> said <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>'s shoes
still reeked of gasoline when he was arrested at his apartment 12
hours after the fire.
   According to immigration records, <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> arrived in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> at <LOCATION>Key West</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>, on <DATE>May 31, 1980</DATE>, as part of the Mariel
boatlift.
   He was detained at <LOCATION>Camp McCoy</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wis.</LOCATION>, then <LOCATION>Fort Chaffee</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ark.</LOCATION>,
until <DATE>Feb. 21, 1981</DATE>, when he was released, said <PERSON>Verne Jervis</PERSON> of the
immigration service.
   He was sent to live with a sponsor family in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. The
agency that handled that placement said it was still looking for
<PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON>' records.
   Gonzalez told federal officials that he was in a Cuban prison
from <DATE>1971</DATE> to <DATE>1974</DATE> for desertion. But that account had not been
confirmed, officials said.
   Jervis said <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> had never applied for permanent residence,
which makes him deportable after doing time for a criminal offense.
</TEXT>
