<HEAD>Social Club Owner Arrested in Fatal Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of an illegal basement nightclub where
six people died in a fire was arrested at a pay phone after police
traced a call he made to a detective to assert his innocence,
authorities said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Domingo Reyes</PERSON>, 37, was charged <DATE>Thursday</DATE> with six counts of
manslaughter and 10 of reckless endangerment in the blaze at the
<LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> club known as The Hole, said Deputy Chief <PERSON>Daniel Ryan</PERSON>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Fire Department</ORGANIZATION> said the blaze <DATE>Sunday</DATE> appeared to be
accidental, but <PERSON>Reyes</PERSON> was held responsible because the club was
illegally operated, authorities said.
   The club served liquor without a license and did not have enough
exits, officials said.
   Six patrons were killed and 33 others injured. The reckless
endangerment counts relate to the 10 most seriously injured, <PERSON>Ryan</PERSON>
said.
   Reyes was arrested after he called police, ran out of change and
gave the number to a detective who promised to call back, said
<PERSON>Ryan</PERSON>. The detective kept him on the line for 35 minutes while
police used the number to locate the phone.
   ``Reyes was explaining (to the detective) he didn't think he'd
done anything wrong,'' said <PERSON>Ryan</PERSON>. ``Basically, he was protesting
his innocence.''
   Police are also looking for <PERSON>Reyes</PERSON>' partner in the club, but <PERSON>Ryan</PERSON>
said he is believed to be out of the country.
   Police had raided The Hole five times since <DATE>March</DATE> and made nine
arrests, said mayoral spokesman <PERSON>Tom Kelly</PERSON>. The steep, narrow
staircase leading down to the club was ``no better than a ladder,''
said <ORGANIZATION>Fire Department</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>John Mulligan</PERSON>.
   Mayor <PERSON>Edward I. Koch</PERSON>, who said <DATE>Monday</DATE> he wanted the city to do
more to close illegal social clubs, described the club, a
50-by-75-foot T-shaped space, as a ``rabbit warren.''
</TEXT>
