<HEAD>Mourners Flood Bronx Funeral Home in Tearful Farewell</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Three women ...,' to UPDATE with at least 15
other people requiring medical assistance. INSERTS 1 graf after
19th graf, `More than ...,' to UPDATE with Honduran government
declaring three days of national mourning, identifying 78 of the
victims as Honduran; picks up 20th graf, `The government ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY7,NY22,HSN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of mourners, many weeping, others
calling for revenge, offered their prayers at a funeral home
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> for 17 victims of the city's deadliest fire in 79 years.
   Officials, meanwhile, began preparations for a grim airlift of
the dead to their Honduran homeland. The <ORGANIZATION>Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> has asked the
<ORGANIZATION>New York National Guard</ORGANIZATION> to help transport the bodies, an aide to
Gov. <PERSON>Mario Cuomo</PERSON> said.
   A funeral Mass <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME> at <ORGANIZATION>St. Joseph's Catholic Church</ORGANIZATION>
drew 1,500 people, while 1,000 others who could not get in stood
outside the church during the service.
   Earlier, outside the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION> funeral home across the street from
<LOCATION>St. Joseph</LOCATION>'s, the street was crowded with people waiting to pay
their respects to the victims. The dead were among 87 people killed
early <DATE>Sunday</DATE> inside the Happy Land social club in the <LOCATION>Bronx</LOCATION>, just
10 blocks away.
   Three women fainted outside the funeral home, collapsing in
front of the crowd waiting to enter. At least 15 others needed
medical assistance.
   <PERSON>Jose Alvarez</PERSON>, mourning his brother <PERSON>Denny</PERSON>, 22, left the <ORGANIZATION>Rivera
Funeral Home</ORGANIZATION> sobbing and clinging to his cousin and a friend.
   Across the street on the steps of the church, <PERSON>Denny</PERSON>'s father
tearfully vented his rage at <PERSON>Julio Gonzalez</PERSON>, 36, the man accused of
setting the fatal fire in a quarrel with an ex-girlfriend.
   ``They ought to take him and give him a public hanging,'' <PERSON>Pedro
Alvarez</PERSON> said. ``People like that don't deserve to live.''
   Two women emerged from the home screaming the names of dead
relatives. Others expressed disbelief their friends were gone.
   ``He doesn't look like him. He looks too old,'' said <PERSON>Katy
Carval</PERSON>, 17, after seeing former classmate <PERSON>Israel Bulnes</PERSON>, 18, who
died with his girlfriend.
   Earlier in the day, family members of the victims met with
<ORGANIZATION>American Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> officials at a public school near the burned-out
red brick building to receive the belongings each victim carried or
wore when the fire struck.
   Outside the school, <PERSON>Carlos Pena</PERSON> clutched a manila envelope that
held a watch, a set of keys, and some cash _ things his brother
<PERSON>Eli</PERSON>, 26, had with him early <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at the doomed Happy Land club.
   The watch came with <ORGANIZATION>Eli</ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Carlos</PERSON> said the
timepiece would now be his. ``It means a lot, a reminder,'' he said.
   Also <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, a civil court hearing did not determine whether
the club operator's widow should replace her husband, <PERSON>Elias Colon</PERSON>,
in an eviction lawsuit brought by the landlord, <ORGANIZATION>One Peach
Associates</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Jay Weiss</PERSON>, husband of actress <PERSON>Kathleen Turner</PERSON>, is part owner of
One Peach, which held a 49-year lease on the building from one of
<LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>'s biggest landlords, <PERSON>Alex DiLorenzo III</PERSON>.
   The court hearing did not address responsibility for the fire or
whether the landlords were aware of a city effort to close the club
because it was illegal and unsafe.
   While wakes were held <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, funeral arrangements still were
being made.
   The Honduran government said it expected the bodies of 75 fire
victims to begin arriving late this week at <LOCATION>San Pedro Sula</LOCATION> in
northwestern <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>.
   More than one-third of the Hondurans were from <LOCATION>Puerto Cortes</LOCATION>, a
<LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> port 135 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Tegucigalpa</LOCATION>, said Information
Minister <PERSON>Nahum Valladares</PERSON>.
   The Honduran government declared three days of national mourning
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, and said 78 victims had been identified as Honduran.
   The government was negotiating with <ORGANIZATION>Eastern Airlines</ORGANIZATION> to take the
bodies from <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Miami</LOCATION>, where they would be transferred to
the Honduran airline Tan-Sahsa, said the minister.
   The airline was working with the <ORGANIZATION>Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> to provide special
fares for relatives wishing to attend the funerals in <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION>,
said spokeswoman <PERSON>Karen Ceremsak</PERSON>. Tan-Sahsa and the <LOCATION>Costa Rican</LOCATION>
carrier <ORGANIZATION>Lacsa</ORGANIZATION> also offered to help, said <ORGANIZATION>Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Larry
Mackler</PERSON>.
   In <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, Rep. <PERSON>Patricia Schroeder</PERSON>, <LOCATION>D-Colo.</LOCATION>, called on the
<ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> to donate use of a transport plane to return fire victims
for burial in their homelands of <LOCATION>Honduras</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Dominican
Republic</LOCATION>.
   ``Providing an <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> plane would be a humanitarian gesture
to the families of the victims,'' she said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>
Secretary <PERSON>Donald Rice</PERSON>. ``Moreover, it would help express <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s
sorrow for the tragedy and our affection for our neighbors in the
hemisphere.''
   An <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> spokesman, Lt. Col. <PERSON>Darrell Hayes</PERSON>, said <PERSON>Rice</PERSON> has
the matter ``under consideration.''
</TEXT>
